{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"confuciusAnalects","displayName":"Analects of Confucius","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"James Legge Translation, 1861","primaryCategory":"Philosophy & Thought","subcategory":"Confucian","audienceTags":["philosophy","ethics"],"sortPriority":44,"itemCount":370,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["book","chapter"],"groupingLabels":["Book","Chapter"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Confucius_Analects.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"analects-1-1","text":"'Is it not delightful to have friends coming from distant quarters?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"analects-1-2","text":"'Is he not a man of complete virtue, who feels no discomposure though men may take no note of him?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"analects-1-3","text":"'The superior man bends his attention to what is radical.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"analects-1-4","text":"'Hold faithfulness and sincerity as first principles.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"analects-1-5","text":"'Have no friends not equal to yourself.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"analects-1-6","text":"'When you have faults, do not fear to abandon them.' CHAP. IX. The philosopher Tsang said, 'Let there be a careful attention to perform the funeral rites to parents, and let them be followed when long gone with the ceremonies of sacrifice;-- then the virtue of the people will resume its proper excellence.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"analects-1-7","text":"Tsze-kung said, 'Our master is benign, upright, courteous, temperate, and complaisant, and thus he gets his information. The master's mode of asking information!-- is it not different from that of other men?' CHAP. XI. The Master said, 'While a man's father is alive, look at the bent of his will; when his father is dead, look at his conduct. If for three years he does not alter from the way of his father, he may be called filial.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"analects-1-8","text":"'Yet it is not to be observed in all cases. If one, knowing how such ease should be prized, manifests it, without regulating it by the rules of propriety, this likewise is not to be done.' CHAP. XIII. The philosopher Yu said, 'When agreements are made according to what is right, what is spoken can be made good. When respect is shown according to what is proper, one keeps far from shame and disgrace. When the parties upon whom a man leans are proper persons to be intimate with, he can make them his guides and masters.' CHAP. XIV. The Master said, 'He who aims to be a man of complete virtue in his food does not seek to gratify his appetite, nor","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"analects-1-9","text":"Tsze-kung replied, 'It is said in the Book of Poetry, \"As you cut and then file, as you carve and then polish.\"-- The meaning is the same, I apprehend, as that which you have just expressed.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"analects-1-10","text":"The Master said, 'With one like Ts'ze, I can begin to talk","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 1.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"analects-2-1","text":"'If they be led by virtue, and uniformity sought to be given them by the rules of propriety, they will have the sense of shame, and moreover will become good.' CHAP. IV. 1. The Master said, 'At fifteen, I had my mind bent on learning.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"analects-2-2","text":"'At thirty, I stood firm.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"analects-2-3","text":"'At forty, I had no doubts.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"analects-2-4","text":"'At fifty, I knew the decrees of Heaven.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"analects-2-5","text":"'At sixty, my ear was an obedient organ for the reception of truth.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"analects-2-6","text":"'At seventy, I could follow what my heart desired, without transgressing what was right.' CHAP. V. 1. Mang I asked what filial piety was. The Master said, 'It is not being disobedient.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"analects-2-7","text":"Soon after, as Fan Ch'ih was driving him, the Master told him, saying, 'Mang-sun asked me what filial piety was, and I answered him,-- \"not being disobedient.\"'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"analects-2-8","text":"Fan Ch'ih said, 'What did you mean?' The Master replied, 'That parents, when alive, be served according to propriety; that, when dead, they should be buried according to propriety; and that they should be sacrificed to according to propriety.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"analects-2-9","text":"'Mark his motives.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"analects-2-10","text":"'Examine in what things he rests.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"analects-2-11","text":"'How can a man conceal his character?","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"analects-2-12","text":"How can a man conceal his character?' CHAP. XI. The Master said, 'If a man keeps cherishing his old knowledge, so as continually to be acquiring new, he may be a teacher of others.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"analects-2-13","text":"The Master said, 'Hear much and put aside the points of which you stand in doubt, while you speak cautiously at the same time of the others:-- then you will afford few occasions for blame. See much and put aside the things which seem perilous, while you are cautious at the same time in carrying the others into practice:-- then you will have few occasions for repentance. When one gives few occasions for blame in his words, and few occasions for repentance in his conduct, he is in the way to get emolument.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"analects-2-14","text":"The Master said, 'What does the Shu-ching say of filial piety?-- \"You are filial, you discharge your brotherly duties. These qualities are displayed in government.\" This then also constitutes the exercise of government. Why must there be THAT-- making one be in the government?' CHAP. XXII. The Master said, 'I do not know how a man without truthfulness is to get on. How can a large carriage be made to go without the cross-bar for yoking the oxen to, or a small carriage without the arrangement for yoking the horses?' CHAP. XXIII. 1. Tsze-chang asked whether the affairs of ten ages after could be known.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"analects-2-15","text":"Confucius said, 'The Yin dynasty followed the regulations of the Hsia: wherein it took from or added to them may be known. The Chau dynasty has followed the regulations of Yin: wherein it took from or added to them may be known. Some other may follow the Chau, but though it should be at the distance of a hundred ages, its affairs may be known.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"analects-2-16","text":"'To see what is right and not to do it is want of courage.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 2.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"analects-3-1","text":"The Master said, 'A great question indeed!","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"analects-3-2","text":"'In festive ceremonies, it is better to be sparing than extravagant.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"analects-3-3","text":"The Master said, 'The business of laying on the colours follows (the preparation of) the plain ground.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"analects-3-4","text":"'Ceremonies then are a subsequent thing?' The Master said, 'It is Shang who can bring out my meaning. Now I can begin to talk about the odes with him.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":29},{"id":"analects-3-5","text":"The Master said, 'I consider my not being present at the sacrifice, as if I did not sacrifice.' CHAP. XIII. 1. Wang-sun Chia asked, saying, 'What is the meaning of the saying, \"It is better to pay court to the furnace than to the south-west corner?\"'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":30},{"id":"analects-3-6","text":"The Master said, 'Not so. He who offends against Heaven has none to whom he can pray.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":31},{"id":"analects-3-7","text":"The Master said, 'Ts'ze, you love the sheep; I love the ceremony.' CHAP. XVII. The Master said, 'The full observance of the rules of propriety in serving one's prince is accounted by people to be flattery.' CHAP. XIX. The Duke Ting asked how a prince should employ his ministers, and how ministers should serve their prince. Confucius replied, 'A prince should employ his minister according to according to the rules of propriety; ministers should serve their prince with faithfulness.' CHAP. XX. The Master said, 'The Kwan Tsu is expressive of enjoyment without being licentious, and of grief without being hurtfully excessive.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":32},{"id":"analects-3-8","text":"When the Master heard it, he said, 'Things that are done, it is needless to speak about; things that have had their course, it is needless to remonstrate about; things that are past, it is needless to blame.' CHAP. XXII. 1. The Master said, 'Small indeed was the capacity of Kwan Chung!'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":33},{"id":"analects-3-9","text":"Some one said, 'Was Kwan Chung parsimonious?' 'Kwan,' was the reply, 'had the San Kwei, and his officers performed no double duties; how can he be considered parsimonious?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":34},{"id":"analects-3-10","text":"'Then, did Kwan Chung know the rules of propriety?' The","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 3.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":35},{"id":"analects-4-1","text":"'If a superior man abandon virtue, how can he fulfil the requirements of that name?","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 4.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":36},{"id":"analects-4-2","text":"'The superior man does not, even for the space of a single meal, act contrary to virtue. In moments of haste, he cleaves to it. In seasons of danger, he cleaves to it.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 4.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":37},{"id":"analects-4-3","text":"'Is any one able for one day to apply his strength to virtue? I have not seen the case in which his strength would be insufficient.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 4.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":38},{"id":"analects-4-4","text":"'Should there possibly be any such case, I have not seen it.' CHAP. VII. The Master said, 'The faults of men are characteristic of the class to which they belong. By observing a man's faults, it may be known that he is virtuous.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 4.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":39},{"id":"analects-4-5","text":"The Master went out, and the other disciples asked, saying,","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 4.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":40},{"id":"analects-5-1","text":"Of Nan Yung he said that if the country were well governed","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":41},{"id":"analects-5-2","text":"The Master said, 'What is the good of being ready with the tongue? They who encounter men with smartnesses of speech for the most part procure themselves hatred. I know not whether he be truly virtuous, but why should he show readiness of the tongue?' CHAP. V. The Master was wishing Ch'i-tiao K'ai to enter on official employment. He replied, 'I am not yet able to rest in the assurance of THIS.' The Master was pleased. CHAP. VI. The Master said, 'My doctrines make no way. I will get upon a raft, and float about on the sea. He that will accompany me will be Yu, I dare say.' Tsze-lu hearing this was glad,","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":42},{"id":"analects-5-3","text":"He asked again, when the Master replied, 'In a kingdom of a thousand chariots, Yu might be employed to manage the military levies, but I do not know whether he be perfectly virtuous.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":43},{"id":"analects-5-4","text":"'And what do you say of Ch'iu?' The Master replied, 'In a city of a thousand families, or a clan of a hundred chariots, Ch'iu might be employed as governor, but I do not know whether he is perfectly virtuous.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":44},{"id":"analects-5-5","text":"'What do you say of Ch'ih?' The Master replied, 'With his sash girt and standing in a court, Ch'ih might be employed to converse with the visitors and guests, but I do not know whether he is perfectly virtuous.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":45},{"id":"analects-5-6","text":"Tsze-kung replied, 'How dare I compare myself with Hui? Hui hears one point and knows all about a subject; I hear one point, and know a second.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":46},{"id":"analects-5-7","text":"The Master said, 'You are not equal to him. I grant you, you are not equal to him.' CHAP. IX. 1. Tsai Yu being asleep during the daytime, the Master said, 'Rotten wood cannot be carved; a wall of dirty earth will not receive the trowel. This Yu!-- what is the use of my reproving him?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":47},{"id":"analects-5-8","text":"The Master said, 'At first, my way with men was to hear their words, and give them credit for their conduct. Now my way is to hear their words, and look at their conduct. It is from Yu that I have learned to make this change.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":48},{"id":"analects-5-9","text":"Tsze-chang proceeded, 'When the officer Ch'ui killed the prince of Ch'i, Ch'an Wan, though he was the owner of forty horses, abandoned them and left the country. Coming to another State, he said, \"They are here like our great officer, Ch'ui,\" and left it. He came to a second State, and with the same observation left it also;-- what do you say of him?' The Master replied, 'He was pure.' 'Was he perfectly virtuous?' 'I do not know. How can he be pronounced perfectly virtuous?' CHAP. XIX. Chi Wan thought thrice, and then acted. When the Master was informed of it, he said, 'Twice may do.' CHAP. XX. The Master said, 'When good order prevailed in his country, Ning Wu acted the part of a wise man. When his country was in disorder, he acted the part of a stupid man. Others may equal his wisdom, but they cannot equal his stupidity.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":49},{"id":"analects-5-10","text":"Tsze-lu said, 'I should like, having chariots and horses, and light fur dresses, to share them with my friends, and though they should spoil them, I would not be displeased.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":50},{"id":"analects-5-11","text":"Yen Yuan said, 'I should like not to boast of my excellence, nor to make a display of my meritorious deeds.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":51},{"id":"analects-5-12","text":"Tsze-lu then said, 'I should like, sir, to hear your wishes.' The Master said, 'They are, in regard to the aged, to give them rest; in regard to friends, to show them sincerity; in regard to the young, to treat them tenderly.' CHAP. XXVI. The Master said, 'It is all over! I have not yet seen one who could perceive his faults, and inwardly accuse himself.' CHAP. XXVII. The Master said, 'In a hamlet of ten families, there may be found one honourable and sincere as I am, but not so fond of learning.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 5.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":52},{"id":"analects-6-1","text":"Chung-kung asked about Tsze-sang Po-tsze. The Master said, 'He may pass. He does not mind small matters.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 6.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":53},{"id":"analects-6-2","text":"Chung-kung said, 'If a man cherish in himself a reverential feeling of the necessity of attention to business, though he may be easy in small matters in his government of the people, that may be allowed. But if he cherish in himself that easy feeling, and also carry it out in his practice, is not such an easy mode of procedure excessive?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 6.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":54},{"id":"analects-6-3","text":"The Master said, 'Yung's words are right.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 6.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":55},{"id":"analects-6-4","text":"The Master said, 'When Ch'ih was proceeding to Ch'i, he had fat horses to his carriage, and wore light furs. I have heard that","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 6.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":56},{"id":"analects-6-5","text":"Yuan Sze being made governor of his town by the Master, he gave him nine hundred measures of grain, but Sze declined them.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 6.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":57},{"id":"analects-6-6","text":"The Master said, 'Do not decline them. May you not give them away in the neighborhoods, hamlets, towns, and villages?' CHAP. IV. The Master, speaking of Chung-kung, said, 'If the calf of a brindled cow be red and horned, although men may not wish to use it, would the spirits of the mountains and rivers put it aside?' CHAP. V. The Master said, 'Such was Hui that for three months there would be nothing in his mind contrary to perfect virtue. The others may attain to this on some days or in some months, but nothing more.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 6.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":58},{"id":"analects-6-7","text":"'Now the man of perfect virtue, wishing to be established himself, seeks also to establish others; wishing to be enlarged himself, he seeks also to enlarge others.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 6.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":59},{"id":"analects-6-8","text":"'To be able to judge of others by what is nigh in ourselves;-- this may be called the art of virtue.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 6.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":60},{"id":"analects-7-1","text":"'Let every attainment in what is good be firmly grasped.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":61},{"id":"analects-7-2","text":"'Let perfect virtue be accorded with.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":62},{"id":"analects-7-3","text":"'Let relaxation and enjoyment be found in the polite arts.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":63},{"id":"analects-7-4","text":"He did not sing on the same day in which he had been weeping. CHAP. X. 1. The Master said to Yen Yuan, 'When called to office, to undertake its duties; when not so called, to lie retired;-- it is only I and you who have attained to this.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":64},{"id":"analects-7-5","text":"Tsze-lu said, 'If you had the conduct of the armies of a great State, whom would you have to act with you?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":65},{"id":"analects-7-6","text":"The Master said, 'I would not have him to act with me, who will unarmed attack a tiger, or cross a river without a boat, dying without any regret. My associate must be the man who proceeds to action full of solicitude, who is fond of adjusting his plans, and then carries them into execution.' CHAP. XI. The Master said, 'If the search for riches is sure to be successful, though I should become a groom with whip in hand to get them, I will do so. As the search may not be successful, I will follow after that which I love.' CHAP. XII. The things in reference to which the Master exercised the greatest caution were -- fasting, war, and sickness.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":66},{"id":"analects-7-7","text":"He went in accordingly, and said, 'What sort of men were Po-i and Shu-ch'i?' 'They were ancient worthies,' said the Master. 'Did they have any repinings because of their course?' The Master again replied, 'They sought to act virtuously, and they did so; what was there for them to repine about?' On this, Tsze-kung went out and said, 'Our Master is not for him.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":67},{"id":"analects-7-8","text":"The Master said, 'Why did you not say to him,-- He is simply a man, who in his eager pursuit (of knowledge) forgets his food, who in the joy of its attainment forgets his sorrows, and who does not perceive that old age is coming on?' CHAP. XIX. The Master said, 'I am not one who was born in the possession of knowledge; I am one who is fond of antiquity, and earnest in seeking it there.' CHAP. XX. The subjects on which the Master did not talk, were-- extraordinary things, feats of strength, disorder, and spiritual beings.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":68},{"id":"analects-7-9","text":"The Master said, 'A good man it is not mine to see; could I see a man possessed of constancy, that would satisfy me.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":69},{"id":"analects-7-10","text":"'Having not and yet affecting to have, empty and yet affecting to be full, straitened and yet affecting to be at ease:-- it is difficult with such characteristics to have constancy.' CHAP. XXVI. The Master angled,-- but did not use a net. He shot,-- but not at birds perching. CHAP. XXVII. The Master said, 'There may be those who act without knowing why. I do not do so. Hearing much and selecting what is good and following it; seeing much and keeping it in memory:-- this is the second style of knowledge.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":70},{"id":"analects-7-11","text":"The Master said, 'I admit people's approach to me without committing myself as to what they may do when they have retired. Why must one be so severe? If a man purify himself to wait upon me, I receive him so purified, without guaranteeing his past conduct.' CHAP. XXIX. The Master said, 'Is virtue a thing remote? I wish to be virtuous, and lo! virtue is at hand.' CHAP. XXX. 1. The minister of crime of Ch'an asked whether the duke Chao knew propriety, and Confucius said, 'He knew propriety.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":71},{"id":"analects-7-12","text":"Confucius having retired, the minister bowed to Wu-ma Ch'i","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":72},{"id":"analects-7-13","text":"Wu-ma Ch'i reported these remarks, and the Master said, 'I am fortunate! If I have any errors, people are sure to know them.' CHAP. XXXI. When the Master was in company with a person who was singing, if he sang well, he would make him repeat the song, while he accompanied it with his own voice. CHAP. XXXII. The Master said, 'In letters I am perhaps equal to other men, but the character of the superior man, carrying out in his conduct what he professes, is what I have not yet attained to.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 7.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":73},{"id":"analects-8-1","text":"'When those who are in high stations perform well all their duties to their relations, the people are aroused to virtue. When old friends are not neglected by them, the people are preserved from meanness.' CHAP. III. The philosopher Tsang being ill, he called to him the disciples of his school, and said, 'Uncover my feet, uncover my hands. It is said in the Book of Poetry, \"We should be apprehensive and cautious, as if on the brink of a deep gulf, as if treading on thin ice,\" and so have I been. Now and hereafter, I know my escape from all injury to my person, O ye, my little children.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":74},{"id":"analects-8-2","text":"Tsang said to him, 'When a bird is about to die, its notes are mournful; when a man is about to die, his words are good.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":75},{"id":"analects-8-3","text":"'There are three principles of conduct which the man of high rank should consider specially important:-- that in his deportment and manner he keep from violence and heedlessness; that in regulating his countenance he keep near to sincerity; and that in his words and tones he keep far from lowness and impropriety. As to such matters as attending to the sacrificial vessels, there are the proper officers for them.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":76},{"id":"analects-8-4","text":"'Perfect virtue is the burden which he considers it is his to sustain;-- is it not heavy? Only with death does his course stop;-- is it not long? CHAP. VIII. 1. The Master said, 'It is by the Odes that the mind is aroused.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":77},{"id":"analects-8-5","text":"'It is by the Rules of Propriety that the character is established.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":78},{"id":"analects-8-6","text":"'It is from Music that the finish is received.' CHAP. IX. The Master said, 'The people may be made to follow a path of action, but they may not be made to understand it.' CHAP. X. The Master said, 'The man who is fond of daring and is dissatisfied with poverty, will proceed to insubordination. So will the man who is not virtuous, when you carry your dislike of him to an extreme.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":79},{"id":"analects-8-7","text":"'Such an one will not enter a tottering State, nor dwell in a disorganized one. When right principles of government prevail in the kingdom, he will show himself; when they are prostrated, he will keep concealed.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":80},{"id":"analects-8-8","text":"'When a country is well-governed, poverty and a mean condition are things to be ashamed of. When a country is ill- governed, riches and honour are things to be ashamed of.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":81},{"id":"analects-8-9","text":"'How majestic was he in the works which he accomplished! How glorious in the elegant regulations which he instituted!' CHAP. XX. 1. Shun had five ministers, and the empire was well-governed.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":82},{"id":"analects-8-10","text":"King Wu said, 'I have ten able ministers.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":83},{"id":"analects-8-11","text":"Confucius said, 'Is not the saying that talents are difficult to find, true? Only when the dynasties of T'ang and Yu met, were they more abundant than in this of Chau, yet there was a woman among them. The able ministers were no more than nine men.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":84},{"id":"analects-8-12","text":"'King Wan possessed two of the three parts of the empire, and with those he served the dynasty of Yin. The virtue of the house of Chau may be said to have reached the highest point indeed.' CHAP. XXI. The Master said, 'I can find no flaw in the character of Yu. He used himself coarse food and drink, but displayed the utmost filial piety towards the spirits. His ordinary garments were poor, but he displayed the utmost elegance in his sacrificial cap and apron. He lived in a low mean house, but expended all his strength on the ditches and water-channels. I can find nothing like a flaw in Yu.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 8.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"8","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":85},{"id":"analects-9-1","text":"The Master heard the observation, and said to his disciples, 'What shall I practise? Shall I practise charioteering, or shall I practise archery? I will practise charioteering.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":86},{"id":"analects-9-2","text":"'The rules of ceremony prescribe the bowing below the hall, but now the practice is to bow only after ascending it. That is arrogant. I continue to bow below the hall, though I oppose the common practice.' CHAP. IV. There were four things from which the Master was entirely free. He had no foregone conclusions, no arbitrary predeterminations, no obstinacy, and no egoism. CHAP. V. 1. The Master was put in fear in K'wang.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":87},{"id":"analects-9-3","text":"He said, 'After the death of King Wan, was not the cause of truth lodged here in me?","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":88},{"id":"analects-9-4","text":"'If Heaven had wished to let this cause of truth perish, then I, a future mortal, should not have got such a relation to that cause. While Heaven does not let the cause of truth perish, what can the people of K'wang do to me?' CHAP. VI. 1. A high officer asked Tsze-kung, saying, 'May we not say that your Master is a sage? How various is his ability!'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":89},{"id":"analects-9-5","text":"Tsze-kung said, 'Certainly Heaven has endowed him unlimitedly. He is about a sage. And, moreover, his ability is various.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":90},{"id":"analects-9-6","text":"The Master heard of the conversation and said, 'Does the high officer know me? When I was young, my condition was low, and therefore I acquired my ability in many things, but they were mean matters. Must the superior man have such variety of ability? He does not need variety of ability.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":91},{"id":"analects-9-7","text":"Lao said, 'The Master said, \"Having no official employment, I acquired many arts.\"'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":92},{"id":"analects-9-8","text":"'The Master, by orderly method, skilfully leads men on. He enlarged my mind with learning, and taught me the restraints of propriety.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":93},{"id":"analects-9-9","text":"'When I wish to give over the study of his doctrines, I cannot do so, and having exerted all my ability, there seems something to stand right up before me; but though I wish to follow and lay hold of it, I really find no way to do so.' CHAP. XI. 1. The Master being very ill, Tsze-lu wished the disciples to act as ministers to him.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":94},{"id":"analects-9-10","text":"During a remission of his illness, he said, 'Long has the conduct of Yu been deceitful! By pretending to have ministers when I have them not, whom should I impose upon? Should I impose upon Heaven?","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":95},{"id":"analects-9-11","text":"'Moreover, than that I should die in the hands of ministers, is it not better that I should die in the hands of you, my disciples? And though I may not get a great burial, shall I die upon the road?' CHAP. XII. Tsze-kung said, 'There is a beautiful gem here. Should I lay it up in a case and keep it? or should I seek for a good price and sell it?' The Master said, 'Sell it! Sell it! But I would wait for one to offer the price.' CHAP. XIII. 1. The Master was wishing to go and live among the nine wild tribes of the east.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":96},{"id":"analects-9-12","text":"Some one said, 'They are rude. How can you do such a thing?' The Master said, 'If a superior man dwelt among them, what rudeness would there be?' CHAP. XIV. The Master said, 'I returned from Wei to Lu, and then the music was reformed, and the pieces in the Royal songs and Praise songs all found their proper places.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":97},{"id":"analects-9-13","text":"'\"He dislikes none, he covets nothing;-- what can he do but what is good!\"'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":98},{"id":"analects-9-14","text":"Tsze-lu kept continually repeating these words of the ode, when the Master said, 'Those things are by no means sufficient to constitute (perfect) excellence.' CHAP. XXVII. The Master said, 'When the year becomes cold, then we know how the pine and the cypress are the last to lose their leaves.' CHAP. XXVIII. The Master said, 'The wise are free from perplexities; the virtuous from anxiety; and the bold from fear.' CHAP. XXIX. The Master said, 'There are some with whom we may study in common, but we shall find them unable to go along","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":99},{"id":"analects-9-15","text":"The Master said, 'It is the want of thought about it. How is it distant?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 9.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"9","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":100},{"id":"analects-10-1","text":"When he was in the prince's ancestorial temple, or in the court, he spoke minutely on every point, but cautiously. CHAP II. 1. When he was waiting at court, in speaking with the great officers of the lower grade, he spake freely, but in a straightforward manner; in speaking with those of the higher grade, he did so blandly, but precisely.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":101},{"id":"analects-10-2","text":"When the ruler was present, his manner displayed respectful uneasiness; it was grave, but self-possessed.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":102},{"id":"analects-10-3","text":"He inclined himself to the other officers among whom he stood, moving his left or right arm, as their position required, but keeping the skirts of his robe before and behind evenly adjusted.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":103},{"id":"analects-10-4","text":"He hastened forward, with his arms like the wings of a bird.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":104},{"id":"analects-10-5","text":"When the guest had retired, he would report to the prince, 'The visitor is not turning round any more.' CHAP. IV. 1. When he entered the palace gate, he seemed to bend his body, as if it were not sufficient to admit him.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":105},{"id":"analects-10-6","text":"When he was standing, he did not occupy the middle of the gate-way; when he passed in or out, he did not tread upon the threshold.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":106},{"id":"analects-10-7","text":"When he was passing the vacant place of the prince, his countenance appeared to change, and his legs to bend under him, and his words came as if he hardly had breath to utter them.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":107},{"id":"analects-10-8","text":"He ascended the reception hall, holding up his robe with both his hands, and his body bent; holding in his breath also, as if he dared not breathe.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":108},{"id":"analects-10-9","text":"When he came out from the audience, as soon as he had descended one step, he began to relax his countenance, and had a satisfied look. When he had got to the bottom of the steps, he advanced rapidly to his place, with his arms like wings, and on occupying it, his manner still showed respectful uneasiness. CHAP. V. 1. When he was carrying the scepter of his ruler, he seemed to bend his body, as if he were not able to bear its weight. He did not hold it higher than the position of the hands in making","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":109},{"id":"analects-10-10","text":"In presenting the presents with which he was charged, he wore a placid appearance.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":110},{"id":"analects-10-11","text":"At his private audience, he looked highly pleased. CHAP. VI. 1. The superior man did not use a deep purple, or a puce colour, in the ornaments of his dress.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":111},{"id":"analects-10-12","text":"Even in his undress, he did not wear anything of a red or reddish colour.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":112},{"id":"analects-10-13","text":"In warm weather, he had a single garment either of coarse or fine texture, but he wore it displayed over an inner garment.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":113},{"id":"analects-10-14","text":"Over lamb's fur he wore a garment of black; over fawn's fur one of white; and over fox's fur one of yellow.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":114},{"id":"analects-10-15","text":"The fur robe of his undress was long, with the right sleeve short.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":115},{"id":"analects-10-16","text":"He required his sleeping dress to be half as long again as his body.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":116},{"id":"analects-10-17","text":"When staying at home, he used thick furs of the fox or the badger.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":117},{"id":"analects-10-18","text":"When he put off mourning, he wore all the appendages of the girdle.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.18 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"18"},"sequenceIndex":118},{"id":"analects-10-19","text":"His under-garment, except when it was required to be of the curtain shape, was made of silk cut narrow above and wide below.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.19 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"19"},"sequenceIndex":119},{"id":"analects-10-20","text":"He did not wear lamb's fur or a black cap, on a visit of condolence.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.20 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"20"},"sequenceIndex":120},{"id":"analects-10-21","text":"On the first day of the month he put on his court robes, and presented himself at court.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.21 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"21"},"sequenceIndex":121},{"id":"analects-10-22","text":"When fasting, he thought it necessary to change his food, and also to change the place where he commonly sat in the apartment. CHAP. VIII. 1. He did not dislike to have his rice finely cleaned, nor to have his minced meat cut quite small.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.22 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"22"},"sequenceIndex":122},{"id":"analects-10-23","text":"He did not eat rice which had been injured by heat or damp and turned sour, nor fish or flesh which was gone. He did not eat what was discoloured, or what was of a bad flavour, nor anything which was ill-cooked, or was not in season.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.23 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"23"},"sequenceIndex":123},{"id":"analects-10-24","text":"He did not eat meat which was not cut properly, nor what was served without its proper sauce.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.24 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"24"},"sequenceIndex":124},{"id":"analects-10-25","text":"Though there might be a large quantity of meat, he would not allow what he took to exceed the due proportion for the rice. It was only in wine that he laid down no limit for himself, but he did not allow himself to be confused by it.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.25 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"25"},"sequenceIndex":125},{"id":"analects-10-26","text":"He did not partake of wine and dried meat bought in the market.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.26 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"26"},"sequenceIndex":126},{"id":"analects-10-27","text":"He was never without ginger when he ate.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.27 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"27"},"sequenceIndex":127},{"id":"analects-10-28","text":"He did not eat much.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.28 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"28"},"sequenceIndex":128},{"id":"analects-10-29","text":"When he had been assisting at the prince's sacrifice, he did not keep the flesh which he received overnight. The flesh of his family sacrifice he did not keep over three days. If kept over three days, people could not eat it.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.29 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"29"},"sequenceIndex":129},{"id":"analects-10-30","text":"When eating, he did not converse. When in bed, he did not speak.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.30 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"30"},"sequenceIndex":130},{"id":"analects-10-31","text":"Although his food might be coarse rice and vegetable soup, he would offer a little of it in sacrifice with a grave, respectful air. CHAP. IX. If his mat was not straight, he did not sit on it. CHAP. X. 1. When the villagers were drinking together, on those who carried staffs going out, he went out immediately after.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.31 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"31"},"sequenceIndex":131},{"id":"analects-10-32","text":"When the villagers were going through their ceremonies to drive away pestilential influences, he put on his court robes and stood on the eastern steps.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.32 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"32"},"sequenceIndex":132},{"id":"analects-10-33","text":"Chi K'ang having sent him a present of physic, he bowed and received it, saying, 'I do not know it. I dare not taste it.' CHAP. XII. The stable being burned down, when he was at court, on his return he said, 'Has any man been hurt?' He did not ask about the horses. CHAP. XIII. 1. When the prince sent him a gift of cooked meat, he would adjust his mat, first taste it, and then give it away to others. When the prince sent him a gift of undressed meat, he would have it cooked, and offer it to the spirits of his ancestors. When the prince sent him a gift of a living animal, he would keep it alive.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.33 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"33"},"sequenceIndex":133},{"id":"analects-10-34","text":"When he was in attendance on the prince and joining in the entertainment, the prince only sacrificed. He first tasted everything.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.34 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"34"},"sequenceIndex":134},{"id":"analects-10-35","text":"When he was ill and the prince came to visit him, he had his head to the east, made his court robes be spread over him, and drew his girdle across them.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.35 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"35"},"sequenceIndex":135},{"id":"analects-10-36","text":"When the prince's order called him, without waiting for his carriage to be yoked, he went at once. CHAP. XIV. When he entered the ancestral temple of the State, he asked about everything. CHAP. XV. 1. When any of his friends died, if he had no relations who could be depended on for the necessary offices, he would say, 'I will bury him.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.36 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"36"},"sequenceIndex":136},{"id":"analects-10-37","text":"When a friend sent him a present, though it might be a carriage and horses, he did not bow.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.37 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"37"},"sequenceIndex":137},{"id":"analects-10-38","text":"The only present for which he bowed was that of the flesh of sacrifice. CHAP. XVI. 1. In bed, he did not lie like a corpse. At home, he did not put on any formal deportment.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.38 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"38"},"sequenceIndex":138},{"id":"analects-10-39","text":"When he saw any one in a mourning dress, though it might be an acquaintance, he would change countenance; when he saw any one wearing the cap of full dress, or a blind person, though he might be in his undress, he would salute them in a ceremonious manner.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.39 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"39"},"sequenceIndex":139},{"id":"analects-10-40","text":"To any person in mourning he bowed forward to the crossbar of his carriage; he bowed in the same way to any one bearing the tables of population.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.40 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"40"},"sequenceIndex":140},{"id":"analects-10-41","text":"When he was at an entertainment where there was an abundance of provisions set before him, he would change countenance and rise up.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.41 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"41"},"sequenceIndex":141},{"id":"analects-10-42","text":"On a sudden clap of thunder, or a violent wind, he would change countenance. CHAP. XVII. 1. When he was about to mount his carriage, he would stand straight, holding the cord.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.42 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"42"},"sequenceIndex":142},{"id":"analects-10-43","text":"When he was in the carriage, he did not turn his head quite round, he did not talk hastily, he did not point with his hands. CHAP. XVIII. 1. Seeing the countenance, it instantly rises. It flies round, and by and by settles.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.43 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"43"},"sequenceIndex":143},{"id":"analects-10-44","text":"The Master said, 'There is the hen-pheasant on the hill bridge. At its season! At its season!' Tsze-lu made a motion to it. Thrice it smelt him and then rose.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 10.44 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"10","chapter":"44"},"sequenceIndex":144},{"id":"analects-11-1","text":"'If I have occasion to use those things, I follow the men of former times.' CHAP. II. 1. The Master said, 'Of those who were with me in Ch'an and Ts'ai, there are none to be found to enter my door.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":145},{"id":"analects-11-2","text":"Distinguished for their virtuous principles and practice, there were Yen Yuan, Min Tsze-ch'ien, Zan Po-niu, and Chung-kung; for their ability in speech, Tsai Wo and Tsze-kung; for their adminis-","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":146},{"id":"analects-11-3","text":"The Master said, 'Every one calls his son his son, whether he has talents or has not talents. There was Li; when he died, he had a coffin but no outer shell. I would not walk on foot to get a shell for him, because, having followed in the rear of the great officers, it was not proper that I should walk on foot.' CHAP. VIII. When Yen Yuan died, the Master said, 'Alas! Heaven is destroying me! Heaven is destroying me!'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":147},{"id":"analects-11-4","text":"'Is it excessive?' said he.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":148},{"id":"analects-11-5","text":"'If I am not to mourn bitterly for this man, for whom should I mourn?' CHAP. X. 1. When Yen Yuan died, the disciples wished to give him a great funeral, and the Master said, 'You may not do so.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":149},{"id":"analects-11-6","text":"The disciples did bury him in great style.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":150},{"id":"analects-11-7","text":"The Master said, 'Hui behaved towards me as his father. I have not been able to treat him as my son. The fault is not mine; it belongs to you, O disciples.' CHAP. XI. Chi Lu asked about serving the spirits of the dead. The Master said, 'While you are not able to serve men, how can you serve their spirits?' Chi Lu added, 'I venture to ask about","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":151},{"id":"analects-11-8","text":"He said, 'Yu, there!-- he will not die a natural death.' CHAP. XIII. 1. Some parties in Lu were going to take down and rebuild the Long Treasury.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":152},{"id":"analects-11-9","text":"Min Tsze-ch'ien said, 'Suppose it were to be repaired after its old style;-- why must it be altered and made anew?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":153},{"id":"analects-11-10","text":"The Master said, 'This man seldom speaks; when he does, he is sure to hit the point.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":154},{"id":"analects-11-11","text":"The other disciples began not to respect Tsze-lu. The Master said, 'Yu has ascended to the hall, though he has not yet passed into the inner apartments.' CHAP. XV. 1. Tsze-kung asked which of the two, Shih or Shang, was the superior. The Master said, 'Shih goes beyond the due mean, and Shang does not come up to it.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":155},{"id":"analects-11-12","text":"'Then,' said Tsze-kung, 'the superiority is with Shih, I suppose.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":156},{"id":"analects-11-13","text":"The Master said, 'To go beyond is as wrong as to fall short.' CHAP. XVI. 1. The head of the Chi family was richer than the duke of Chau had been, and yet Ch'iu collected his imposts for him, and increased his wealth.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":157},{"id":"analects-11-14","text":"The Master said, 'He is no disciple of mine. My little children, beat the drum and assail him.' CHAP. XVII. 1. Ch'ai is simple.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":158},{"id":"analects-11-15","text":"Shan is dull.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":159},{"id":"analects-11-16","text":"Shih is specious.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":160},{"id":"analects-11-17","text":"Yu is coarse. CHAP. XVIII. 1. The Master said, 'There is Hui! He has nearly attained to perfect virtue. He is often in want.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":161},{"id":"analects-11-18","text":"'Ts'ze does not acquiesce in the appointments of Heaven, and his goods are increased by him. Yet his judgments are often correct.' CHAP. XIX. Tsze-chang asked what were the characteristics of","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.18 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"18"},"sequenceIndex":162},{"id":"analects-11-19","text":"The Master said, 'I thought you would ask about some extraordinary individuals, and you only ask about Yu and Ch'iu!","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.19 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"19"},"sequenceIndex":163},{"id":"analects-11-20","text":"'What is called a great minister, is one who serves his prince according to what is right, and when he finds he cannot do so, retires.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.20 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"20"},"sequenceIndex":164},{"id":"analects-11-21","text":"'Now, as to Yu and Ch'iu, they may be called ordinary ministers.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.21 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"21"},"sequenceIndex":165},{"id":"analects-11-22","text":"Tsze-zan said, 'Then they will always follow their chief;-- will they?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.22 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"22"},"sequenceIndex":166},{"id":"analects-11-23","text":"The Master said, 'In an act of parricide or regicide, they would not follow him.' CHAP. XXIV. 1. Tsze-lu got Tsze-kao appointed governor of Pi.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.23 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"23"},"sequenceIndex":167},{"id":"analects-11-24","text":"The Master said, 'You are injuring a man's son.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.24 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"24"},"sequenceIndex":168},{"id":"analects-11-25","text":"Tsze-lu said, 'There are (there) common people and officers; there are the altars of the spirits of the land and grain. Why must one read books before he can be considered to have learned?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.25 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"25"},"sequenceIndex":169},{"id":"analects-11-26","text":"The Master said, 'It is on this account that I hate your glib-tongued people.' CHAP. XXV. 1. Tsze-lu, Tsang Hsi, Zan Yu, and Kung-hsi Hwa were sitting by the Master.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.26 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"26"},"sequenceIndex":170},{"id":"analects-11-27","text":"He said to them, 'Though I am a day or so older than you, do not think of that.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.27 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"27"},"sequenceIndex":171},{"id":"analects-11-28","text":"'From day to day you are saying, \"We are not known.\" If some ruler were to know you, what would you like to do?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.28 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"28"},"sequenceIndex":172},{"id":"analects-11-29","text":"Tsze-lu hastily and lightly replied, 'Suppose the case of a State of ten thousand chariots; let it be straitened between other large States; let it be suffering from invading armies; and to this let there be added a famine in corn and in all vegetables:-- if I were intrusted with the government of it, in three years' time I could make the people to be bold, and to recognise the rules of righteous conduct.' The Master smiled at him.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.29 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"29"},"sequenceIndex":173},{"id":"analects-11-30","text":"Turning to Yen Yu, he said, 'Ch'iu, what are your wishes?' Ch'iu replied, 'Suppose a state of sixty or seventy li square, or one of fifty or sixty, and let me have the government of it;-- in three years' time, I could make plenty to abound among the people. As to teaching them the principles of propriety, and music, I must wait for the rise of a superior man to do that.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.30 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"30"},"sequenceIndex":174},{"id":"analects-11-31","text":"'What are your wishes, Ch'ih,' said the Master next to Kung- hsi Hwa. Ch'ih replied, 'I do not say that my ability extends to these things, but I should wish to learn them. At the services of the ancestral temple, and at the audiences of the princes with the sovereign, I should like, dressed in the dark square-made robe and the black linen cap, to act as a small assistant.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.31 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"31"},"sequenceIndex":175},{"id":"analects-11-32","text":"Last of all, the Master asked Tsang Hsi, 'Tien, what are your wishes?' Tien, pausing as he was playing on his lute, while it was yet twanging, laid the instrument aside, and rose. 'My wishes,' he said, 'are different from the cherished purposes of these three gentlemen.' 'What harm is there in that?' said the Master; 'do you also, as well as they, speak out your wishes.' Tien then said, 'In this, the last month of spring, with the dress of the season all complete, along with five or six young men who have assumed the cap, and six or seven boys, I would wash in the I, enjoy the breeze among the rain altars, and return home singing.' The Master heaved a sigh and said, 'I give my approval to Tien.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.32 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"32"},"sequenceIndex":176},{"id":"analects-11-33","text":"The three others having gone out, Tsang Hsi remained behind, and said, 'What do you think of the words of these three friends?' The Master replied, 'They simply told each one his wishes.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.33 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"33"},"sequenceIndex":177},{"id":"analects-11-34","text":"Hsi pursued, 'Master, why did you smile at Yu?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.34 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"34"},"sequenceIndex":178},{"id":"analects-11-35","text":"He was answered, 'The management of a State demands the rules of propriety. His words were not humble; therefore I smiled at him.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.35 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"35"},"sequenceIndex":179},{"id":"analects-11-36","text":"Hsi again said, 'But was it not a State which Ch'iu proposed for himself?' The reply was, 'Yes; did you ever see a territory of sixty or seventy li or one of fifty or sixty, which was not a State?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.36 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"36"},"sequenceIndex":180},{"id":"analects-11-37","text":"Once more, Hsi inquired, 'And was it not a State which Ch'ih proposed for himself?' The Master again replied, 'Yes; who but princes have to do with ancestral temples, and with audiences but the sovereign? If Ch'ih were to be a small assistant in these services, who could be a great one?","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 11.37 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"11","chapter":"37"},"sequenceIndex":181},{"id":"analects-12-1","text":"Yen Yuan said, 'I beg to ask the steps of that process.' The Master replied, 'Look not at what is contrary to propriety; listen not to what is contrary to propriety; speak not what is contrary to propriety; make no movement which is contrary to propriety.' Yen Yuan then said, 'Though I am deficient in intelligence and vigour, I will make it my business to practise this lesson.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":182},{"id":"analects-12-2","text":"The Master said, 'The man of perfect virtue is cautious and slow in his speech.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":183},{"id":"analects-12-3","text":"'Cautious and slow in his speech!' said Niu;-- 'is this what is meant by perfect virtue?' The Master said, 'When a man feels the difficulty of doing, can he be other than cautious and slow in speaking?' CHAP. IV. 1. Sze-ma Niu asked about the superior man. The Master said, 'The superior man has neither anxiety nor fear.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":184},{"id":"analects-12-4","text":"'Being without anxiety or fear!' said Nui;-- 'does this constitute what we call the superior man?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":185},{"id":"analects-12-5","text":"The Master said, 'When internal examination discovers nothing wrong, what is there to be anxious about, what is there to fear?' CHAP. V. 1. Sze-ma Niu, full of anxiety, said, 'Other men all have their brothers, I only have not.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":186},{"id":"analects-12-6","text":"Tsze-hsia said to him, 'There is the following saying which I have heard:--","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":187},{"id":"analects-12-7","text":"'\"Death and life have their determined appointment; riches and honours depend upon Heaven.\"","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":188},{"id":"analects-12-8","text":"'Let the superior man never fail reverentially to order his own conduct, and let him be respectful to others and observant of propriety:-- then all within the four seas will be his brothers. What has the superior man to do with being distressed because he has no brothers?' CHAP. VI. Tsze-chang asked what constituted intelligence. The Master said, 'He with whom neither slander that gradually soaks into the mind, nor statements that startle like a wound in the flesh, are successful, may be called intelligent indeed. Yea, he with whom neither soaking slander, nor startling statements, are successful, may be called farseeing.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":189},{"id":"analects-12-9","text":"Tsze-kung said, 'If it cannot be helped, and one of these must be dispensed with, which of the three should be foregone first?' 'The military equipment,' said the Master.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":190},{"id":"analects-12-10","text":"Tsze-kung again asked, 'If it cannot be helped, and one of the remaining two must be dispensed with, which of them should be foregone?' The Master answered, 'Part with the food. From of old, death has been the lot of all men; but if the people have no faith in their rulers, there is no standing for the state.' CHAP. VIII. 1. Chi Tsze-ch'ang said, 'In a superior man it is only the substantial qualities which are wanted;-- why should we seek for ornamental accomplishments?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":191},{"id":"analects-12-11","text":"Tsze-kung said, 'Alas! Your words, sir, show you to be a superior man, but four horses cannot overtake the tongue.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":192},{"id":"analects-12-12","text":"Ornament is as substance; substance is as ornament. The hide of a tiger or a leopard stripped of its hair, is like the hide of a dog or a goat stripped of its hair.' CHAP. IX. 1. The Duke Ai inquired of Yu Zo, saying, 'The year is one of scarcity, and the returns for expenditure are not sufficient;-- what is to be done?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":193},{"id":"analects-12-13","text":"Yu Zo replied to him, 'Why not simply tithe the people?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":194},{"id":"analects-12-14","text":"'With two tenths, said the duke, 'I find it not enough;-- how could I do with that system of one tenth?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":195},{"id":"analects-12-15","text":"Yu Zo answered, 'If the people have plenty, their prince will not be left to want alone. If the people are in want, their prince cannot enjoy plenty alone.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":196},{"id":"analects-12-16","text":"'You love a man and wish him to live; you hate him and wish him to die. Having wished him to live, you also wish him to die. This is a case of delusion.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":197},{"id":"analects-12-17","text":"'\"It may not be on account of her being rich, yet you come to make a difference.\"' CHAP. XI. 1. The Duke Ching, of Ch'i, asked Confucius about government.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":198},{"id":"analects-12-18","text":"Confucius replied, 'There is government, when the prince is prince, and the minister is minister; when the father is father, and the son is son.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.18 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"18"},"sequenceIndex":199},{"id":"analects-12-19","text":"'Good!' said the duke; 'if, indeed; the prince be not prince, the minister not minister, the father not father, and the son not son, although I have my revenue, can I enjoy it?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.19 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"19"},"sequenceIndex":200},{"id":"analects-12-20","text":"Tsze-lu never slept over a promise. CHAP. XIII. The Master said, 'In hearing litigations, I am like any other body. What is necessary, however, is to cause the people to have no litigations.' CHAP. XIV. Tsze-chang asked about government. The Master said, 'The art of governing is to keep its affairs before the mind without weariness, and to practise them with undeviating consistency.' CHAP. XV. The Master said, 'By extensively studying all learning, and keeping himself under the restraint of the rules of propriety, one may thus likewise not err from what is right.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.20 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"20"},"sequenceIndex":201},{"id":"analects-12-21","text":"The Master said, 'What is it you call being distinguished?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.21 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"21"},"sequenceIndex":202},{"id":"analects-12-22","text":"Tsze-chang replied, 'It is to be heard of through the State, to be heard of throughout his clan.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.22 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"22"},"sequenceIndex":203},{"id":"analects-12-23","text":"The Master said, 'That is notoriety, not distinction.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.23 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"23"},"sequenceIndex":204},{"id":"analects-12-24","text":"'Now the man of distinction is solid and straightforward, and loves righteousness. He examines people's words, and looks at their countenances. He is anxious to humble himself to others. Such a man will be distinguished in the country; he will be distinguished in his clan.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.24 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"24"},"sequenceIndex":205},{"id":"analects-12-25","text":"'As to the man of notoriety, he assumes the appearance of","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.25 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"25"},"sequenceIndex":206},{"id":"analects-12-26","text":"The Master said, 'Truly a good question!","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.26 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"26"},"sequenceIndex":207},{"id":"analects-12-27","text":"'If doing what is to be done be made the first business, and success a secondary consideration;-- is not this the way to exalt virtue? To assail one's own wickedness and not assail that of others;-- is not this the way to correct cherished evil? For a morning's anger to disregard one's own life, and involve that of his parents;-- is not this a case of delusion?' CHAP. XXII. 1. Fan Ch'ih asked about benevolence. The Master said, 'It is to love all men.' He asked about knowledge. The Master said, 'It is to know all men.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.27 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"27"},"sequenceIndex":208},{"id":"analects-12-28","text":"Fan Ch'ih did not immediately understand these answers.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.28 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"28"},"sequenceIndex":209},{"id":"analects-12-29","text":"The Master said, 'Employ the upright and put aside all the crooked;-- in this way the crooked can be made to be upright.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.29 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"29"},"sequenceIndex":210},{"id":"analects-12-30","text":"Fan Ch'ih retired, and, seeing Tsze-hsia, he said to him, 'A Little while ago, I had an interview with our Master, and asked him about knowledge. He said, 'Employ the upright, and put aside all the crooked;-- in this way, the crooked will be made to be upright.' What did he mean?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.30 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"30"},"sequenceIndex":211},{"id":"analects-12-31","text":"Tsze-hsia said, 'Truly rich is his saying!","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.31 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"31"},"sequenceIndex":212},{"id":"analects-12-32","text":"'Shun, being in possession of the kingdom, selected from among all the people, and employed Kao-yao, on which all who were devoid of virtue disappeared. T'ang, being in possession of the kingdom, selected from among all the people, and employed I Yin, and all who were devoid of virtue disappeared.' CHAP. XXIII. Tsze-kung asked about friendship. The Master said, 'Faithfully admonish your friend, and skillfully lead him on. If you find him impracticable, stop. Do not disgrace yourself.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 12.32 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"12","chapter":"32"},"sequenceIndex":213},{"id":"analects-13-1","text":"He requested further instruction, and was answered, 'Be not weary (in these things).' CHAP. II. 1. Chung-kung, being chief minister to the Head of the Chi family, asked about government. The Master said, 'Employ","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":214},{"id":"analects-13-2","text":"Chung-kung said, 'How shall I know the men of virtue and talent, so that I may raise them to office?' He was answered, 'Raise to office those whom you know. As to those whom you do not know, will others neglect them?' CHAP. III. 1. Tsze-lu said, 'The ruler of Wei has been waiting for you, in order with you to administer the government. What will you consider the first thing to be done?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":215},{"id":"analects-13-3","text":"The Master replied, 'What is necessary is to rectify names.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":216},{"id":"analects-13-4","text":"'So, indeed!' said Tsze-lu. 'You are wide of the mark! Why must there be such rectification?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":217},{"id":"analects-13-5","text":"The Master said, 'How uncultivated you are, Yu! A superior man, in regard to what he does not know, shows a cautious reserve.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":218},{"id":"analects-13-6","text":"'If names be not correct, language is not in accordance with","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":219},{"id":"analects-13-7","text":"'When affairs cannot be carried on to success, proprieties and music will not flourish. When proprieties and music do not flourish, punishments will not be properly awarded. When punishments are not properly awarded, the people do not know how to move hand or foot.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":220},{"id":"analects-13-8","text":"'Therefore a superior man considers it necessary that the names he uses may be spoken appropriately, and also that what he speaks may be carried out appropriately. What the superior man requires, is just that in his words there may be nothing incorrect.' CHAP. IV. 1. Fan Ch'ih requested to be taught husbandry. The Master said, 'I am not so good for that as an old husbandman.' He","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":221},{"id":"analects-13-9","text":"Fan Ch'ih having gone out, the Master said, 'A small man, indeed, is Fan Hsu!","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":222},{"id":"analects-13-10","text":"If a superior love propriety, the people will not dare not to be reverent. If he love righteousness, the people will not dare not to submit to his example. If he love good faith, the people will not dare not to be sincere. Now, when these things obtain, the people from all quarters will come to him, bearing their children on their backs;-- what need has he of a knowledge of husbandry?' CHAP. V. The Master said, 'Though a man may be able to recite the three hundred odes, yet if, when intrusted with a governmental charge, he knows not how to act, or if, when sent to any quarter on a mission, he cannot give his replies unassisted, notwithstanding the extent of his learning, of what practical use is it?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":223},{"id":"analects-13-11","text":"The Master observed, 'How numerous are the people!'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":224},{"id":"analects-13-12","text":"Yu said, 'Since they are thus numerous, what more shall be done for them?' 'Enrich them,' was the reply.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":225},{"id":"analects-13-13","text":"'And when they have been enriched, what more shall be done?' The Master said, 'Teach them.' CHAP. X. The Master said, 'If there were (any of the princes) who would employ me, in the course of twelve months, I should have done something considerable. In three years, the government would be perfected.' CHAP. XI. The Master said, '\"If good men were to govern a country in succession for a hundred years, they would be able to transform the violently bad, and dispense with capital punishments.\" True indeed is this saying!' CHAP. XII. The Master said, 'If a truly royal ruler were to arise, it would still require a generation, and then virtue would prevail.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":226},{"id":"analects-13-14","text":"'There is a saying, however, which people have-- \"To be a prince is difficult; to be a minister is not easy.\"","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":227},{"id":"analects-13-15","text":"'If a ruler knows this,-- the difficulty of being a prince,-- may there not be expected from this one sentence the prosperity of his country?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":228},{"id":"analects-13-16","text":"The duke then said, 'Is there a single sentence which can ruin a country?' Confucius replied, 'Such an effect as that cannot be expected from one sentence. There is, however, the saying which people have-- \"I have no pleasure in being a prince, but only in that no one can offer any opposition to what I say!\"","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":229},{"id":"analects-13-17","text":"'If a ruler's words be good, is it not also good that no one oppose them? But if they are not good, and no one opposes them, may there not be expected from this one sentence the ruin of his country?' CHAP. XVI. 1. The Duke of Sheh asked about government.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":230},{"id":"analects-13-18","text":"The Master said, 'Good government obtains, when those who are near are made happy, and those who are far off are attracted.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.18 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"18"},"sequenceIndex":231},{"id":"analects-13-19","text":"Confucius said, 'Among us, in our part of the country, those who are upright are different from this. The father conceals the misconduct of the son, and the son conceals the misconduct of the father. Uprightness is to be found in this.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.19 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"19"},"sequenceIndex":232},{"id":"analects-13-20","text":"Tsze-kung pursued, 'I venture to ask who may be placed in the next lower rank?' And he was told, 'He whom the circle of his relatives pronounce to be filial, whom his fellow-villagers and neighbours pronounce to be fraternal.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.20 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"20"},"sequenceIndex":233},{"id":"analects-13-21","text":"Again the disciple asked, 'I venture to ask about the class still next in order.' The Master said, 'They are determined to be sincere in what they say, and to carry out what they do. They are obstinate little men. Yet perhaps they may make the next class.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.21 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"21"},"sequenceIndex":234},{"id":"analects-13-22","text":"Tsze-kung finally inquired, 'Of what sort are those of the present day, who engage in government?' The Master said 'Pooh! they are so many pecks and hampers, not worth being taken into account.' CHAP. XXI. The Master said, 'Since I cannot get men pursuing the due medium, to whom I might communicate my instructions, I must find the ardent and the cautiously-decided. The ardent will advance and lay hold of truth; the cautiously-decided will keep themselves from what is wrong.' CHAP. XXII. 1. The Master said, 'The people of the south have a saying-- \"A man without constancy cannot be either a wizard or a doctor.\" Good!","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.22 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"22"},"sequenceIndex":235},{"id":"analects-13-23","text":"'Inconstant in his virtue, he will be visited with disgrace.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.23 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"23"},"sequenceIndex":236},{"id":"analects-13-24","text":"The Master said, 'This arises simply from not attending to the prognostication.' CHAP. XXIII. The Master said, 'The superior man is affable, but not adulatory; the mean man is adulatory, but not affable.' CHAP. XXIV. Tsze-kung asked, saying, 'What do you say of a man who is loved by all the people of his neighborhood?' The Master replied, 'We may not for that accord our approval of him.' 'And what do you say of him who is hated by all the people of his neighborhood?' The Master said, 'We may not for that conclude that he is bad. It is better than either of these cases that the good in the neighborhood love him, and the bad hate him.' CHAP. XXV. The Master said, 'The superior man is easy to serve and difficult to please. If you try to please him in any way which is not accordant with right, he will not be pleased. But in his","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 13.24 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"13","chapter":"24"},"sequenceIndex":237},{"id":"analects-14-1","text":"The Master said, 'This may be regarded as the achievement of what is difficult. But I do not know that it is to be deemed perfect virtue.' CHAP. III. The Master said, 'The scholar who cherishes the love of comfort is not fit to be deemed a scholar.' CHAP. IV. The Master said, 'When good government prevails in a state, language may be lofty and bold, and actions the same. When bad government prevails, the actions may be lofty and bold, but the language may be with some reserve.' CHAP. V. The Master said, 'The virtuous will be sure to speak correctly, but those whose speech is good may not always be virtuous. Men of principle are sure to be bold, but those who are bold may not always be men of principle.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":238},{"id":"analects-14-2","text":"He asked about Tsze-hsi. The Master said, 'That man! That man!'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":239},{"id":"analects-14-3","text":"He asked about Kwan Chung. 'For him,' said the Master, 'the city of Pien, with three hundred families, was taken from the chief of the Po family, who did not utter a murmuring word, though, to the end of his life, he had only coarse rice to eat.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":240},{"id":"analects-14-4","text":"He then added, 'But what is the necessity for a complete man of the present day to have all these things? The man, who in the","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":241},{"id":"analects-14-5","text":"Kung-ming Chia replied, 'This has arisen from the reporters going beyond the truth.-- My master speaks when it is the time to speak, and so men do not get tired of his speaking. He laughs when there is occasion to be joyful, and so men do not get tired of his laughing. He takes when it is consistent with righteousness to do so, and so men do not get tired of his taking.' The Master said, 'So! But is it so with him?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":242},{"id":"analects-14-6","text":"The Master said, 'The Duke Hwan assembled all the princes together, and that not with weapons of war and chariots:-- it was all through the influence of Kwan Chung. Whose beneficence was like his? Whose beneficence was like his?' CHAP. XVIII. 1. Tsze-kung said, 'Kwan Chung, I apprehend, was wanting in virtue. When the Duke Hwan caused his brother Chiu to be killed, Kwan Chung was not able to die with him. Moreover, he became prime minister to Hwan.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":243},{"id":"analects-14-7","text":"The Master said, 'Kwan Chung acted as prime minister to the Duke Hwan, made him leader of all the princes, and united and rectified the whole kingdom. Down to the present day, the people enjoy the gifts which he conferred. But for Kwan Chung, we should now be wearing our hair unbound, and the lappets of our coats buttoning on the left side.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":244},{"id":"analects-14-8","text":"'Will you require from him the small fidelity of common","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":245},{"id":"analects-14-9","text":"The Master, having heard of it, said, 'He deserved to be considered WAN (the accomplished).' CHAP. XX. 1. The Master was speaking about the unprincipled course of the duke Ling of Wei, when Ch'i K'ang said, 'Since he is of such a character, how is it he does not lose his State?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":246},{"id":"analects-14-10","text":"Confucius said, 'The Chung-shu Yu has the superintendence of his guests and of strangers; the litanist, T'o, has the management","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":247},{"id":"analects-14-11","text":"Confucius bathed, went to court, and informed the duke Ai, saying, 'Chan Hang has slain his sovereign. I beg that you will undertake to punish him.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":248},{"id":"analects-14-12","text":"The duke said, 'Inform the chiefs of the three families of it.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":249},{"id":"analects-14-13","text":"Confucius retired, and said, 'Following in the rear of the great officers, I did not dare not to represent such a matter, and my prince says, \"Inform the chiefs of the three families of it.\"'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":250},{"id":"analects-14-14","text":"He went to the chiefs, and informed them, but they would not act. Confucius then said, 'Following in the rear of the great officers, I did not dare not to represent such a matter.' CHAP. XXIII. Tsze-lu asked how a ruler should be served. The Master said, 'Do not impose on him, and, moreover, withstand him to his face.' CHAP. XXIV. The Master said, 'The progress of the superior man is upwards; the progress of the mean man is downwards.' CHAP. XXV. The Master said, 'In ancient times, men learned with a view to their own improvement. Now-a-days, men learn with a view to the approbation of others.' CHAP. XXVI. 1. Chu Po-yu sent a messenger with friendly inquiries to Confucius.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":251},{"id":"analects-14-15","text":"Confucius sat with him, and questioned him. 'What,' said he, 'is your master engaged in?' The messenger replied, 'My master is","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":252},{"id":"analects-14-16","text":"Tsze-kung said, 'Master, that is what you yourself say.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":253},{"id":"analects-14-17","text":"Confucius said, 'I do not dare to play the part of such a talker, but I hate obstinacy.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":254},{"id":"analects-14-18","text":"The Master said, 'With what then will you recompense kindness?","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.18 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"18"},"sequenceIndex":255},{"id":"analects-14-19","text":"'Recompense injury with justice, and recompense kindness with kindness.' CHAP. XXXVII. 1. The Master said, 'Alas! there is no one that knows me.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.19 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"19"},"sequenceIndex":256},{"id":"analects-14-20","text":"Tsze-kung said, 'What do you mean by thus saying-- that no one knows you?' The Master replied, 'I do not murmur against","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.20 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"20"},"sequenceIndex":257},{"id":"analects-14-21","text":"The Master said, 'If my principles are to advance, it is so ordered. If they are to fall to the ground, it is so ordered. What can the Kung-po Liao do where such ordering is concerned?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.21 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"21"},"sequenceIndex":258},{"id":"analects-14-22","text":"Some retire from particular states.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.22 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"22"},"sequenceIndex":259},{"id":"analects-14-23","text":"Some retire because of disrespectful looks.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.23 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"23"},"sequenceIndex":260},{"id":"analects-14-24","text":"Some retire because of contradictory language.' CHAP. XL.  The Master said, 'Those who have done this are seven men.' CHAP. XLI. Tsze-lu happening to pass the night in Shih-man, the gatekeeper said to him, 'Whom do you come from?' Tsze-lu said, 'From Mr. K'ung.' 'It is he,-- is it not?'-- said the other, 'who knows the impracticable nature of the times and yet will be doing in them.' CHAP. XLII. 1. The Master was playing, one day, on a musical stone in Wei, when a man, carrying a straw basket, passed the door","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.24 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"24"},"sequenceIndex":261},{"id":"analects-14-25","text":"A little while after, he added, 'How contemptible is the one-ideaed obstinacy those sounds display! When one is taken no notice of, he has simply at once to give over his wish for public employment. \"Deep water must be crossed with the clothes on; shallow water may be crossed with the clothes held up.\"'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.25 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"25"},"sequenceIndex":262},{"id":"analects-14-26","text":"The Master said, 'How determined is he in his purpose! But this is not difficult!' CHAP. XLIII. 1. Tsze-chang said, 'What is meant when the Shu says that Kao-tsung, while observing the usual imperial mourning, was for three years without speaking?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.26 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"26"},"sequenceIndex":263},{"id":"analects-14-27","text":"The Master said, 'Why must Kao-tsung be referred to as an example of this? The ancients all did so. When the sovereign died, the officers all attended to their several duties, taking instructions from the prime minister for three years.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.27 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"27"},"sequenceIndex":264},{"id":"analects-14-28","text":"The Master said, 'I observe that he is fond of occupying the seat of a full-grown man; I observe that he walks shoulder to shoulder with his elders. He is not one who is seeking to make progress in learning. He wishes quickly to become a man.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 14.28 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"14","chapter":"28"},"sequenceIndex":265},{"id":"analects-15-1","text":"When he was in Chan, their provisions were exhausted, and his followers became so ill that they were unable to rise.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":266},{"id":"analects-15-2","text":"Tsze-lu, with evident dissatisfaction, said, 'Has the superior man likewise to endure in this way?' The Master said, 'The superior man may indeed have to endure want, but the mean man, when he is in want, gives way to unbridled license.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":267},{"id":"analects-15-3","text":"Tsze-kung replied, 'Yes,-- but perhaps it is not so?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":268},{"id":"analects-15-4","text":"'No,' was the answer; 'I seek a unity all-pervading.' CHAP. III. The Master said, 'Yu, those who know virtue are few.' CHAP. IV. The Master said, 'May not Shun be instanced as having governed efficiently without exertion? What did he do? He did nothing but gravely and reverently occupy his royal seat.' CHAP. V. 1. Tsze-chang asked how a man should conduct himself, so as to be everywhere appreciated.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":269},{"id":"analects-15-5","text":"The Master said, 'Let his words be sincere and truthful, and his actions honourable and careful;-- such conduct may be practised among the rude tribes of the South or the North. If his words be","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":270},{"id":"analects-15-6","text":"'When he is standing, let him see those two things, as it were, fronting him. When he is in a carriage, let him see them attached to the yoke. Then may he subsequently carry them into practice.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":271},{"id":"analects-15-7","text":"Tsze-chang wrote these counsels on the end of his sash. CHAP. VI. 1. The Master said, 'Truly straightforward was the historiographer Yu. When good government prevailed in his State, he was like an arrow. When bad government prevailed, he was like an arrow.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":272},{"id":"analects-15-8","text":"A superior man indeed is Chu Po-yu! When good government prevails in his state, he is to be found in office. When bad government prevails, he can roll his principles up, and keep them in his breast.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":273},{"id":"analects-15-9","text":"The Master said, 'Follow the seasons of Hsia.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":274},{"id":"analects-15-10","text":"'Ride in the state carriage of Yin.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":275},{"id":"analects-15-11","text":"'Wear the ceremonial cap of Chau.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":276},{"id":"analects-15-12","text":"'Let the music be the Shao with its pantomimes.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":277},{"id":"analects-15-13","text":"Banish the songs of Chang, and keep far from specious talkers. The songs of Chang are licentious; specious talkers are dangerous.' CHAP. XI. The Master said, 'If a man take no thought about what is distant, he will find sorrow near at hand.' CHAP. XII. The Master said, 'It is all over! I have not seen one who loves virtue as he loves beauty.' CHAP. XIII. The Master said, 'Was not Tsang Wan like one who had stolen his situation? He knew the virtue and the talents","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":278},{"id":"analects-15-14","text":"'This people supplied the ground why the three dynasties pursued the path of straightforwardness.' CHAP. XXV. The Master said, 'Even in my early days, a historiographer would leave a blank in his text, and he who had a horse would lend him to another to ride. Now, alas! there are no such things.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":279},{"id":"analects-15-15","text":"'When his knowledge is sufficient to attain, and he has virtue enough to hold fast, if he cannot govern with dignity, the people will not respect him.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":280},{"id":"analects-15-16","text":"'When his knowledge is sufficient to attain, and he has virtue enough to hold fast; when he governs also with dignity, yet if he try to move the people contrary to the rules of propriety:-- full excellence is not reached.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":281},{"id":"analects-15-17","text":"The Music-master, Mien, having gone out, Tsze-chang asked, saying. 'Is it the rule to tell those things to the Music- master?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":282},{"id":"analects-15-18","text":"The Master said, 'Yes. This is certainly the rule for those who lead the blind.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 15.18 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"15","chapter":"18"},"sequenceIndex":283},{"id":"analects-16-1","text":"Zan Yu and Chi-lu had an interview with Confucius, and said, 'Our chief, Chi, is going to commence operations against Chwan-yu.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":284},{"id":"analects-16-2","text":"Confucius said, 'Ch'iu, is it not you who are in fault here?","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":285},{"id":"analects-16-3","text":"'Now, in regard to Chwan-yu, long ago, a former king appointed its ruler to preside over the sacrifices to the eastern Mang; moreover, it is in the midst of the territory of our State; and its ruler is a minister in direct connexion with the sovereign:-- What has your chief to do with attacking it?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":286},{"id":"analects-16-4","text":"Zan Yu said, 'Our master wishes the thing; neither of us two ministers wishes it.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":287},{"id":"analects-16-5","text":"Confucius said, 'Ch'iu, there are the words of Chau Zan,-- \"When he can put forth his ability, he takes his place in the ranks of office; when he finds himself unable to do so, he retires from it. How can he be used as a guide to a blind man, who does not support him when tottering, nor raise him up when fallen?\"","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":288},{"id":"analects-16-6","text":"'And further, you speak wrongly. When a tiger or rhinoceros escapes from his cage; when a tortoise or piece of jade is injured in its repository:-- whose is the fault?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":289},{"id":"analects-16-7","text":"Zan Yu said, 'But at present, Chwan-yu is strong and near to Pi; if our chief do not now take it, it will hereafter be a sorrow to his descendants.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":290},{"id":"analects-16-8","text":"Confucius said. 'Ch'iu, the superior man hates that declining to say-- \"I want such and such a thing,\" and framing explanations for the conduct.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":291},{"id":"analects-16-9","text":"'I have heard that rulers of States and chiefs of families are not troubled lest their people should be few, but are troubled lest they should not keep their several places; that they are not troubled with fears of poverty, but are troubled with fears of a want of contented repose among the people in their several places. For when the people keep their several places, there will be no poverty; when harmony prevails, there will be no scarcity of people; and when there is such a contented repose, there will be no rebellious upsettings.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":292},{"id":"analects-16-10","text":"'So it is.-- Therefore, if remoter people are not submissive, all","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":293},{"id":"analects-16-11","text":"'Now, here are you, Yu and Ch'iu, assisting your chief. Remoter people are not submissive, and, with your help, he cannot attract them to him. In his own territory there are divisions and downfalls, leavings and separations, and, with your help, he cannot preserve it.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":294},{"id":"analects-16-12","text":"'And yet he is planning these hostile movements within the State.-- I am afraid that the sorrow of the Chi-sun family will not be on account of Chwan-yu, but will be found within the screen of their own court.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":295},{"id":"analects-16-13","text":"'When right principles prevail in the kingdom, government will not be in the hands of the Great officers.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":296},{"id":"analects-16-14","text":"'When right principles prevail in the kingdom, there will be no discussions among the common people.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":297},{"id":"analects-16-15","text":"'The mean man does not know the ordinances of Heaven, and consequently does not stand in awe of them. He is disrespectful to great men. He makes sport of the words of sages.' CHAP. IX. Confucius said, 'Those who are born with the possession of knowledge are the highest class of men. Those who learn, and so, readily, get possession of knowledge, are the next.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":298},{"id":"analects-16-16","text":"'Living in retirement to study their aims, and practising","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":299},{"id":"analects-16-17","text":"'Is not that saying illustrated by this?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":300},{"id":"analects-16-18","text":"Po-yu replied, 'No. He was standing alone once, when I passed below the hall with hasty steps, and said to me, \"Have you learned the Odes?\" On my replying \"Not yet,\" he added, \"If you do not learn the Odes, you will not be fit to converse with.\" I retired and studied the Odes.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.18 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"18"},"sequenceIndex":301},{"id":"analects-16-19","text":"'Another day, he was in the same way standing alone, when I passed by below the hall with hasty steps, and said to me, 'Have you learned the rules of Propriety?' On my replying 'Not yet,' he added, 'If you do not learn the rules of Propriety, your character cannot be established.' I then retired, and learned the rules of Propriety.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.19 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"19"},"sequenceIndex":302},{"id":"analects-16-20","text":"'I have heard only these two things from him.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.20 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"20"},"sequenceIndex":303},{"id":"analects-16-21","text":"Ch'ang K'ang retired, and, quite delighted, said, 'I asked one thing, and I have got three things. I have heard about the Odes. I have heard about the rules of Propriety. I have also heard that the superior man maintains a distant reserve towards his son.' CHAP. XIV. The wife of the prince of a state is called by him FU ZAN. She calls herself HSIAO T'UNG. The people of the State call","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 16.21 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"16","chapter":"21"},"sequenceIndex":304},{"id":"analects-17-1","text":"Ho said to Confucius, 'Come, let me speak with you.' He then asked, 'Can he be called benevolent who keeps his jewel in his","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":305},{"id":"analects-17-2","text":"Well pleased and smiling, he said, 'Why use an ox knife to kill a fowl?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":306},{"id":"analects-17-3","text":"Tsze-yu replied, 'Formerly, Master, I heard you say,-- \"When the man of high station is well instructed, he loves men; when the man of low station is well instructed, he is easily ruled.\"'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":307},{"id":"analects-17-4","text":"The Master said, 'My disciples, Yen's words are right. What I said was only in sport.' CHAP. V. Kung-shan Fu-zao, when he was holding Pi, and in an attitude of rebellion, invited the Master to visit him, who was rather inclined to go.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":308},{"id":"analects-17-5","text":"Tsze-lu was displeased, and said, 'Indeed, you cannot go! Why must you think of going to see Kung-shan?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":309},{"id":"analects-17-6","text":"The Master said, 'Can it be without some reason that he has invited ME? If any one employ me, may I not make an eastern Chau?' CHAP. VI. Tsze-chang asked Confucius about perfect virtue. Confucius said, 'To be able to practise five things everywhere under heaven constitutes perfect virtue.' He begged to ask what they were, and was told, 'Gravity, generosity of soul, sincerity, earnestness, and kindness. If you are grave, you will not be treated with disrespect. If you are generous, you will win all. If you are sincere, people will repose trust in you. If you are earnest, you will accomplish much. If you are kind, this will enable you to employ the services of others.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":310},{"id":"analects-17-7","text":"Tsze-lu said, 'Master, formerly I have heard you say, \"When a man in his own person is guilty of doing evil, a superior man will not associate with him.\" Pi Hsi is in rebellion, holding possession of Chung-mau; if you go to him, what shall be said?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":311},{"id":"analects-17-8","text":"The Master said, 'Yes, I did use these words. But is it not said, that, if a thing be really hard, it may be ground without being made thin? Is it not said, that, if a thing be really white, it may be steeped in a dark fluid without being made black?","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":312},{"id":"analects-17-9","text":"'Am I a bitter gourd! How can I be hung up out of the way of being eaten?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":313},{"id":"analects-17-10","text":"'Sit down, and I will tell them to you.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":314},{"id":"analects-17-11","text":"'There is the love of being benevolent without the love of learning;-- the beclouding here leads to a foolish simplicity. There is the love of knowing without the love of learning;-- the beclouding here leads to dissipation of mind. There is the love of being sincere without the love of learning;-- the beclouding here leads to an injurious disregard of consequences. There is the love of straightforwardness without the love of learning;-- the beclouding here leads to rudeness. There is the love of boldness without the love of learning;-- the beclouding here leads to insubordination. There is the love of firmness without the love of learning;-- the beclouding here leads to extravagant conduct.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":315},{"id":"analects-17-12","text":"'The Odes serve to stimulate the mind.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":316},{"id":"analects-17-13","text":"'They may be used for purposes of self-contemplation.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":317},{"id":"analects-17-14","text":"'They teach the art of sociability.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":318},{"id":"analects-17-15","text":"'They show how to regulate feelings of resentment.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":319},{"id":"analects-17-16","text":"'From them you learn the more immediate duty of serving one's father, and the remoter one of serving one's prince.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":320},{"id":"analects-17-17","text":"'From them we become largely acquainted with the names of birds, beasts, and plants.' CHAP. X. The Master said to Po-yu, 'Do you give yourself to the Chau-nan and the Shao-nan. The man who has not studied the Chau-nan and the Shao-nan, is like one who stands with his face right against a wall. Is he not so?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":321},{"id":"analects-17-18","text":"'While they have not got their aims, their anxiety is how to get them. When they have got them, their anxiety is lest they should lose them.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.18 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"18"},"sequenceIndex":322},{"id":"analects-17-19","text":"'When they are anxious lest such things should be lost, there is nothing to which they will not proceed.' CHAP. XVI. 1. The Master said, 'Anciently, men had three failings, which now perhaps are not to be found.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.19 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"19"},"sequenceIndex":323},{"id":"analects-17-20","text":"'The high-mindedness of antiquity showed itself in a disregard of small things; the high-mindedness of the present day shows itself in wild license. The stern dignity of antiquity showed itself in grave reserve; the stern dignity of the present day shows itself in quarrelsome perverseness. The stupidity of antiquity showed itself in straightforwardness; the stupidity of the present day shows itself in sheer deceit.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.20 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"20"},"sequenceIndex":324},{"id":"analects-17-21","text":"Tsze-kung said, 'If you, Master, do not speak, what shall we, your disciples, have to record?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.21 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"21"},"sequenceIndex":325},{"id":"analects-17-22","text":"The Master said, 'Does Heaven speak? The four seasons pursue their courses, and all things are continually being produced, but does Heaven say anything?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.22 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"22"},"sequenceIndex":326},{"id":"analects-17-23","text":"'If the superior man,' said he, 'abstains for three years from the observances of propriety, those observances will be quite lost. If for three years he abstains from music, music will be ruined.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.23 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"23"},"sequenceIndex":327},{"id":"analects-17-24","text":"'Within a year the old grain is exhausted, and the new grain has sprung up, and, in procuring fire by friction, we go through all the changes of wood for that purpose. After a complete year, the mourning may stop.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.24 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"24"},"sequenceIndex":328},{"id":"analects-17-25","text":"The Master said, 'If you were, after a year, to eat good rice, and wear embroidered clothes, would you feel at ease?' 'I should,' replied Wo.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.25 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"25"},"sequenceIndex":329},{"id":"analects-17-26","text":"The Master said, 'If you can feel at ease, do it. But a superior man, during the whole period of mourning, does not enjoy pleasant food which he may eat, nor derive pleasure from music which he may hear. He also does not feel at ease, if he is comfortably lodged. Therefore he does not do what you propose. But now you feel at ease and may do it.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.26 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"26"},"sequenceIndex":330},{"id":"analects-17-27","text":"Tsai Wo then went out, and the Master said, 'This shows Yu's want of virtue. It is not till a child is three years old that it is allowed to leave the arms of its parents. And the three years' mourning is universally observed throughout the empire. Did Yu enjoy the three years' love of his parents?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.27 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"27"},"sequenceIndex":331},{"id":"analects-17-28","text":"The Master then inquired, 'Ts'ze, have you also your hatreds?' Tsze-kung replied, 'I hate those who pry out matters, and ascribe the knowledge to their wisdom. I hate those who are only not modest, and think that they are valourous. I hate those who make known secrets, and think that they are straightforward.' CHAP. XXV. The Master said, 'Of all people, girls and servants are the most difficult to behave to. If you are familiar with them, they lose their humility. If you maintain a reserve towards them, they are discontented.' CHAP. XXVI. The Master said, 'When a man at forty is the object of dislike, he will always continue what he is.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 17.28 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"17","chapter":"28"},"sequenceIndex":332},{"id":"analects-18-1","text":"Confucius said, 'The Yin dynasty possessed these three men of virtue.' CHAP. II. Hui of Liu-hsia being chief criminal judge, was thrice dismissed from his office. Some one said to him, 'Is it not yet time for you, sir, to leave this?' He replied, 'Serving men in an upright way, where shall I go to, and not experience such a thrice- repeated","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":333},{"id":"analects-18-2","text":"Confucius alighted and wished to converse with him, but Chieh-yu hastened away, so that he could not talk with him. CHAP. VI. 1. Ch'ang-tsu and Chieh-ni were at work in the field together, when Confucius passed by them, and sent Tsze-lu to inquire for the ford.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":334},{"id":"analects-18-3","text":"Ch'ang-tsu said, 'Who is he that holds the reins in the carriage there?' Tsze-lu told him, 'It is K'ung Ch'iu.' 'Is it not K'ung Ch'iu of Lu?' asked he. 'Yes,' was the reply, to which the other rejoined, 'He knows the ford.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":335},{"id":"analects-18-4","text":"Tsze-lu then inquired of Chieh-ni, who said to him, 'Who","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":336},{"id":"analects-18-5","text":"Tsze-lu went and reported their remarks, when the Master observed with a sigh, 'It is impossible to associate with birds and beasts, as if they were the same with us. If I associate not with these people,-- with mankind,-- with whom shall I associate? If right principles prevailed through the empire, there would be no use for me to change its state.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":337},{"id":"analects-18-6","text":"Tsze-lu joined his hands across his breast, and stood before him.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":338},{"id":"analects-18-7","text":"The old man kept Tsze-lu to pass the night in his house, killed a fowl, prepared millet, and feasted him. He also introduced to him his two sons.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":339},{"id":"analects-18-8","text":"Next day, Tsze-lu went on his way, and reported his adventure. The Master said, 'He is a recluse,' and sent Tsze-lu back to see him again, but when he got to the place, the old man was gone.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":340},{"id":"analects-18-9","text":"Tsze-lu then said to the family, 'Not to take office is not","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":341},{"id":"analects-18-10","text":"The Master said, 'Refusing to surrender their wills, or to submit to any taint in their persons;-- such, I think, were Po-i and Shu-ch'i.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":342},{"id":"analects-18-11","text":"'It may be said of Hui of Liu-hsia, and of Shao-lien, that they surrendered their wills, and submitted to taint in their persons,","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":343},{"id":"analects-18-12","text":"'It may be said of Yu-chung and I-yi, that, while they hid themselves in their seclusion, they gave a license to their words; but, in their persons, they succeeded in preserving their purity, and, in their retirement, they acted according to the exigency of the times.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":344},{"id":"analects-18-13","text":"'I am different from all these. I have no course for which I am predetermined, and no course against which I am predetermined.' CHAP. IX. 1. The grand music master, Chih, went to Ch'i.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.13 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"13"},"sequenceIndex":345},{"id":"analects-18-14","text":"Kan, the master of the band at the second meal, went to Ch'u. Liao, the band master at the third meal, went to Ts'ai. Chueh, the band master at the fourth meal, went to Ch'in.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.14 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"14"},"sequenceIndex":346},{"id":"analects-18-15","text":"Fang-shu, the drum master, withdrew to the north of the river.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.15 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"15"},"sequenceIndex":347},{"id":"analects-18-16","text":"Wu, the master of the hand drum, withdrew to the Han.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.16 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"16"},"sequenceIndex":348},{"id":"analects-18-17","text":"Yang, the assistant music master, and Hsiang, master of the musical stone, withdrew to an island in the sea. CHAP. X. The duke of Chau addressed his son, the duke of Lu, saying, 'The virtuous prince does not neglect his relations. He does not cause the great ministers to repine at his not employing them. Without some great cause, he does not dismiss from their offices the members of old families. He does not seek in one man talents for every employment.' CHAP. XI. To Chau belonged the eight officers, Po-ta, Po-","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 18.17 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"18","chapter":"17"},"sequenceIndex":349},{"id":"analects-19-1","text":"Tsze-hsia heard of the remark and said, 'Alas! Yen Yu is wrong. According to the way of the superior man in teaching, what departments are there which he considers of prime importance, and delivers? what are there which he considers of secondary importance, and allows himself to be idle about? But as in the case of plants, which are assorted according to their classes, so he deals with his disciples. How can the way of a superior man be such as to make fools of any of them? Is it not the sage alone, who can unite in one the beginning and the consummation of learning?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 19.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"19","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":350},{"id":"analects-19-2","text":"Tsze-kung replied, 'The doctrines of Wan and Wu have not yet fallen to the ground. They are to be found among men. Men of talents and virtue remember the greater principles of them, and others, not possessing such talents and virtue, remember the smaller. Thus, all possess the doctrines of Wan and Wu. Where could our Master go that he should not have an opportunity of learning them? And yet what necessity was there for his having a regular master?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 19.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"19","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":351},{"id":"analects-19-3","text":"Tsze-fu Ching-po reported the observation to Tsze-kung, who said, 'Let me use the comparison of a house and its encompassing wall. My wall only reaches to the shoulders. One may peep over it, and see whatever is valuable in the apartments.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 19.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"19","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":352},{"id":"analects-19-4","text":"'The wall of my Master is several fathoms high. If one do not find the door and enter by it, he cannot see the ancestral temple with its beauties, nor all the officers in their rich array.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 19.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"19","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":353},{"id":"analects-19-5","text":"'But I may assume that they are few who find the door. Was not the observation of the chief only what might have been expected?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 19.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"19","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":354},{"id":"analects-19-6","text":"Tsze-kung said to him, 'For one word a man is often deemed to be wise, and for one word he is often deemed to be foolish. We ought to be careful indeed in what we say.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 19.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"19","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":355},{"id":"analects-19-7","text":"'Our Master cannot be attained to, just in the same way as the heavens cannot be gone up to by the steps of a stair.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 19.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"19","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":356},{"id":"analects-19-8","text":"'Were our Master in the position of the ruler of a State or the chief of a Family, we should find verified the description which has been given of a sage's rule:-- he would plant the people, and forthwith they would be established; he would lead them on, and forthwith they would follow him; he would make them happy, and forthwith multitudes would resort to his dominions; he would stimulate them, and forthwith they would be harmonious. While he lived, he would be glorious. When he died, he would be bitterly lamented. How is it possible for him to be attained to?'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 19.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"19","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":357},{"id":"analects-20-1","text":"Shun also used the same language in giving charge to Yu.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":358},{"id":"analects-20-2","text":"T'ang said, 'I the child Li, presume to use a dark-coloured victim, and presume to announce to Thee, O most great and sovereign God, that the sinner I dare not pardon, and thy ministers, O God, I do not keep in obscurity. The examination of them is by thy mind, O God. If, in my person, I commit offences, they are not to be attributed to you, the people of the myriad regions. If you in the myriad regions commit offences, these offences must rest on my person.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":359},{"id":"analects-20-3","text":"Chau conferred great gifts, and the good were enriched.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":360},{"id":"analects-20-4","text":"'Although he has his near relatives, they are not equal to my virtuous men. The people are throwing blame upon me, the One man.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":361},{"id":"analects-20-5","text":"He carefully attended to the weights and measures, examined the body of the laws, restored the discarded officers, and the good government of the kingdom took its course.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":362},{"id":"analects-20-6","text":"He revived States that had been extinguished, restored families whose line of succession had been broken, and called to office those who had retired into obscurity, so that throughout the kingdom the hearts of the people turned towards him.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":363},{"id":"analects-20-7","text":"What he attached chief importance to, were the food of the people, the duties of mourning, and sacrifices.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.7 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"7"},"sequenceIndex":364},{"id":"analects-20-8","text":"By his generosity, he won all. By his sincerity, he made the people repose trust in him. By his earnest activity, his achievements were great. By his justice, all were delighted.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.8 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"8"},"sequenceIndex":365},{"id":"analects-20-9","text":"Tsze-chang said, 'What is meant by being beneficent without great expenditure?' The Master replied, 'When the person in authority makes more beneficial to the people the things from which","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.9 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"9"},"sequenceIndex":366},{"id":"analects-20-10","text":"Tsze-chang then asked, 'What are meant by the four bad things?' The Master said, 'To put the people to death without having instructed them;-- this is called cruelty. To require from them, suddenly, the full tale of work, without having given them warning;-- this is called oppression. To issue orders as if without urgency, at first, and, when the time comes, to insist on them with severity;-- this is called injury. And, generally, in the giving pay","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.10 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"10"},"sequenceIndex":367},{"id":"analects-20-11","text":"'Without an acquaintance with the rules of Propriety, it is impossible for the character to be established.","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.11 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"11"},"sequenceIndex":368},{"id":"analects-20-12","text":"'Without knowing the force of words, it is impossible to know men.'","author":"Confucius","source":"Analects 20.12 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:analects"],"groups":{"book":"20","chapter":"12"},"sequenceIndex":369}]}